In adopting any rule or regulation, the Department shall consider among other things:
Existing physical conditions;
The character of an affected specific area;
Zoning;
The nature of any existing receiving body of water; and
The technical feasibility and economic reasonableness of measuring or reducing a particular type of water pollution.

The Department by rule or regulation, shall:
Identify all hazardous substances that are controlled hazardous substances governed by this subtitle;
Set standards and describe tests to identify lethal, toxic, and other injurious effects of controlled hazardous substances;
Set minimum design standards for controlled hazardous substance facilities;
Establish types and quantities of controlled hazardous substances that may be disposed of;
Establish procedures for monitoring the generation, transportation, treatment, storage, or disposal of controlled hazardous substances;
Set minimum requirements for the operation, maintenance, monitoring, reporting, and supervision of any controlled hazardous substance facility;
Set requirements for receiving and applying for facility permits;
Set standards for determining bond values and fees under this subtitle;
Set health and safety standards that relate specifically to the site of a controlled hazardous substance facility after consideration of, among other things, the following:
Geology;
Seismology;
Hydrology;
Demography; and
Climatology; and
By June 30, 1991, adopt by regulation a revised State Hazardous Substance Response Plan that establishes standards and procedures for actions taken under §§ 7-220 and 7-222 of this subtitle.

The revised State Hazardous Substance Response Plan shall at a minimum include:
Methods for discovering and investigating sites at which hazardous substances have been disposed of or otherwise come to be located;
Methods for evaluating any releases or threats of releases which pose substantial danger to the public health or the environment;
Factors to be considered in determining the type of response action which will be implemented, including the cost of implementing, maintaining, and operating the remedy; and
Methods and criteria for determining the appropriate extent of removal, remedy, and other measures authorized by this title.
